%U A395248 4,4,8,6,6,2,7,1,1,1,0,5,5,9,3,1,8,2
%N A395248 Sprague-Grundy values for the octal game .007.
%C A395248 In the octal game .007, a move removes exactly 3 tokens from a heap and may leave the remaining tokens as zero, one, or two nonempty heaps.
%C A395248 .007 is one of the unsolved octal games: whether the sequence is eventually periodic is unknown (cf. Flammenkamp's tables and R. K. Guy's list of unsolved problems in combinatorial games).
%C A395248 Values computed through n = 2^30 = 1073741824 by the submitter (2026), extending A. Flammenkamp's computation, which reached 2^28. The last "rare" value in Flammenkamp's sparse-space sense occurs at n = 5029983; no further rare values occur through 2^30. The maximum value through 2^30 is 1689, at n = 248902927.
%H A395248 Tyler Satchel Orden, <a href="/A395248/b395248.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..10000</a>
%H A395248 Achim Flammenkamp, <a href="http://wwwhomes.uni-bielefeld.de/achim/octal.html">Sprague-Grundy values of octal games</a>.
%e A395248 a(3) = 1: from a heap of 3 the only move removes all three tokens, reaching the zero position, so the Grundy value is mex{0} = 1.
%o A395248 (Python)
%o A395248 def gvals(N):
%o A395248     G = [0, 0, 0]
%o A395248     for n in range(3, N+1):
%o A395248         s = n - 3
%o A395248         S = {0} if n == 3 else set()
%o A395248         if s >= 1: S.add(G[s])
%o A395248         for i in range(1, s//2 + 1): S.add(G[i] ^ G[s-i])
%o A395248         m = 0
%o A395248         while m in S: m += 1
%o A395248         G.append(m)
%o A395248     return G
%Y A395248 Cf. A002186 (Kayles), A002187 (Dawson's chess), A002188 (Grundy's game).
%K A395248 nonn,new
%O A395248 0,7
